Ahead of the 2023 general elections, Rev. (Dr) John Agboire, President and General Overseer, Saint Emmanuel Spiritual Church of Christ International, Cherubim and Seraphim, Ketu, Lagos, has urged politicians to do away with politics of bitterness for the good of the nation. Agboire, who spoke during the church’s prayer programme for the nation, stressed that the time had come for the nation’s political leaders to shun do-or-die politics, but should work together in peace and harmony for the development of the nation. The cleric, who lamented the going intrigues among major political parties because of their conventions and choice of leaders and candidates, maintained that their actions and utterances had been heating the polity. Cleric Charges Leaders Not To Rely On Personal Knowledge Ending Domestic Violence, Bias Against Women He reminded them that elections should be in the spirit of ‘o victor, no vanquished’, adding that national interests should be uppermost in their minds. The cleric said that politicians should think of ways to tackle the nation’s problems and visit possible cause of challenge confronting the nation such as terrorism, poor economy, ethnicity, ritual killings, with the latest being the toxic fuel crisis. He urged the political leaders to caution themselves to avoid the wrath of God’s falling upon them, stressing, “Nigeria is a Lord’s chosen nation.” He said the hand of God was about to move in the nation, “He will shake those involved in toxic fuel importation and other fuel-related crises, terrorism, poor national economy, among others.”